{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/background-information/prevalence/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"d4c20af9-820c-52a4-a7e3-24612493b406","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 0ae2fe30-4036-4961-83f7-85da502fe65c --><h2>How common is it?</h2><!-- end field 0ae2fe30-4036-4961-83f7-85da502fe65c -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 1dd03ad9-9d2e-4644-a921-b1504344a155 --><!-- begin field 89ebcaba-0eff-4a0c-af92-3e372bb9ded6 --><p><strong>There are limited and variable data on the prevalence of shift work disorder and jet lag disorder in the literature, and there are individual differences in people's susceptibility to these conditions </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Atkinson, 2014</a>]<strong>.</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Shift work disorder</strong><ul><li>The European Working Conditions Survey in 2015 found that 21% of all employees reported working shifts, and 19% worked nights at least once a month [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Parent-Thirion, 2017</a>].</li><li>About 20–30% of shift workers report insufficient sleep and excessive sleepiness in relation to working night and early morning shifts [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Kecklund, 2016</a>].</li><li>In a questionnaire-based study of oil rig workers (n = 103), 23.3% met the criteria for shift work disorder [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Waage, 2009</a>].</li><li>A US telephone interview study (n = 3283 interviews) states that 8% of people working rotating shifts and 14% of night shift workers met the criteria for shift work disorder compared with day shift workers [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Drake, 2004</a>].</li><li>An Australian telephone interview study (n = 1163) found the prevalence of shift work disorder was 32.1% among night shift workers [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Di Milia, 2013</a>].</li></ul></li><li><strong>Jet lag disorder</strong><ul><li>A review article states that is is possible that one-third of all travellers do not experience jet lag, and there is variation between people in the rate of adaptation between time zones for those who are affected [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Arendt, 2018</a>].</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 89ebcaba-0eff-4a0c-af92-3e372bb9ded6 --><!-- end item 1dd03ad9-9d2e-4644-a921-b1504344a155 -->","topic":{"id":"3964f7a0-31e0-5fbb-acd2-28c331f8537e","topicId":"00508bc9-f2ae-4b62-92b6-6813013390e7","topicName":"Sleep disorders - shift work and jet lag","slug":"sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag","lastRevised":"Last revised in November 2019","chapters":[{"id":"75b83b6f-3a17-5dc7-aaaf-e1b6b03327b4","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"a06c50c6-432a-5239-ac77-63d42196c27b","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"e323be68-8cbf-5d0d-8e67-715bbd68f4fe","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"3e71c356-1580-53be-a318-f61bddebbe31","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"161f4a52-fee2-5c49-b8b5-e7e55898959d","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"2410dfe4-334f-5bb0-bb78-718734524edd","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measure